<h1 class="doc-page-title">Getting started with COMPASS</h1>
<p class="doc-page-lead">A beginner-friendly guide to help you understand and start using COMPASS effectively.</p>

<h2 id="welcome">Welcome to COMPASS</h2>

<p>This guide will help you get started with COMPASS, whether you're managing product delivery, tracking operational performance, or both. We'll walk you through the key areas of the system and show you how to accomplish common tasks.</p>

<div class="alert alert-success">
    <p class="mb-0"><i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> <strong>New to COMPASS?</strong> Don't worry! This guide is designed to help you understand the system step by step. Take your time to explore each section.</p>
</div>

<hr class="my-4">

<h2 id="what-is-compass">What is COMPASS?</h2>

<p>COMPASS (Compliance and Management Performance Assurance Support System) is DfE's platform for:</p>

<div class="row mt-3">
    <div class="col-md-6 mb-3">
        <div class="card border-primary h-100">
            <div class="card-body">
                <h3 class="h6"><i class="fas fa-chart-line text-primary"></i> Delivery reporting</h3>
                <p class="mb-0">Track how your products and services are performing, submit metrics, and demonstrate compliance with standards.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-6 mb-3">
        <div class="card border-info h-100">
            <div class="card-body">
                <h3 class="h6"><i class="fas fa-shield-alt text-info"></i> Operational reporting</h3>
                <p class="mb-0">Manage risks, issues, actions, and milestones (known as RAID) to keep your projects and products on track.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<p class="mt-3">Think of COMPASS as your central hub for product governance and performance tracking. It brings together all the information you need to manage products effectively.</p>

<hr class="my-4">

<h2 id="first-login">First login and setup</h2>

<h3 class="h5 mt-4">Step 1: Access COMPASS</h3>
<ol>
    <li>Navigate to the COMPASS URL in your web browser</li>
    <li>You'll be signed in automatically using your DfE Azure Entra ID credentials</li>
    <li>You'll arrive at your personalised dashboard</li>
</ol>

<div class="alert alert-info">
    <p class="mb-0"><i class="fas fa-info-circle"></i> If you don't have access to COMPASS, contact your line manager or the COMPASS support team.</p>
</div>

<h3 class="h5 mt-4">Step 2: Configure your preferences</h3>
<p>Before diving in, it's helpful to set up your preferences so COMPASS shows you the most relevant information.</p>

<ol>
    <li>Click the <strong>user icon</strong> in the top right corner</li>
    <li>Select <strong>My settings</strong> from the dropdown</li>
    <li>In the preferences page:
        <ul>
            <li>Select your <strong>preferred business areas</strong> by checking the relevant boxes</li>
            <li>This will automatically filter views to show items from those areas</li>
            <li>You can always override this to view all items</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>Click <strong>Save preferences</strong></li>
</ol>

<div class="alert alert-success">
    <p class="mb-0"><i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> <strong>Why set preferences?</strong> When you select preferred business areas, COMPASS automatically filters lists to show items relevant to your work. This helps you focus without manually filtering each time you use the system.</p>
</div>

<h3 class="h5 mt-4">Step 3: Explore the navigation</h3>

<p>COMPASS has two main navigation areas:</p>

<h4 class="h6 mt-3">Left sidebar (main navigation)</h4>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Home:</strong> Your personalised dashboard</li>
    <li><strong>Delivery reporting:</strong> Product performance metrics and operational reports</li>
    <li><strong>Enterprise reporting:</strong> Enterprise-level metrics and functional standards</li>
    <li><strong>Reports:</strong> RAID analysis and portfolio reports</li>
    <li><strong>Product governance:</strong> Products, risks, issues, actions, and milestones</li>
    <li><strong>Administration:</strong> System settings (administrators only)</li>
</ul>

<h4 class="h6 mt-3">Top navigation bar</h4>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Home icon:</strong> Return to your dashboard</li>
    <li><strong>Documentation:</strong> Access this help documentation</li>
    <li><strong>Help:</strong> Additional support resources</li>
    <li><strong>Dark mode toggle:</strong> Switch between light and dark themes</li>
    <li><strong>User menu:</strong> Access your settings and profile</li>
</ul>

<hr class="my-4">

<h2 id="understanding-areas">Understanding the main areas of COMPASS</h2>

<p>COMPASS has two main areas of work that serve different but complementary purposes:</p>

<div class="row mt-4">
    <div class="col-lg-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card border-primary h-100">
            <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
                <h3 class="h6 mb-0"><i class="fas fa-chart-line"></i> Delivery reporting</h3>
            </div>
            <div class="card-body">
                <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Track and report on how well your products and services are performing.</p>
                
                <p class="h6 mt-3">What you'll do here:</p>
                <ul class="mb-0">
                    <li>Submit performance metrics (user satisfaction, service availability, etc.)</li>
                    <li>Track metrics over time</li>
                    <li>View performance trends</li>
                    <li>Report on service delivery</li>
                    <li>Demonstrate compliance with functional standards</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="col-lg-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card border-info h-100">
            <div class="card-header bg-info text-white">
                <h3 class="h6 mb-0"><i class="fas fa-shield-alt"></i> Operational reporting (RAID)</h3>
            </div>
            <div class="card-body">
                <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Manage the day-to-day challenges and activities that keep your products and projects running smoothly.</p>
                
                <p class="h6 mt-3">What you'll do here:</p>
                <ul class="mb-0">
                    <li>Track <strong>Risks</strong> - Things that might go wrong</li>
                    <li>Log <strong>Issues</strong> - Problems that have occurred</li>
                    <li>Manage <strong>Actions</strong> - Tasks that need doing</li>
                    <li>Monitor <strong>Milestones</strong> - Key deliverables and deadlines</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<hr class="my-4">

<h2 id="delivery-reporting">Delivery reporting: Tracking product performance</h2>

<p>Delivery reporting helps you track how well your products and services are performing. This is where you submit metrics, view trends, and demonstrate that you're meeting service standards.</p>

<h3 class="h5 mt-4">Finding your products</h3>

<ol>
    <li>Navigate to <strong>Delivery reporting</strong> in the left sidebar</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Operational reports</strong></li>
    <li>You'll see a list of products - find yours in the list</li>
    <li>Click on your product to view its dashboard</li>
</ol>

<div class="alert alert-info">
    <p class="mb-0"><i class="fas fa-info-circle"></i> <strong>Can't see your product?</strong> Product information comes from the FIPS CMS system. If your product isn't listed, check that it's been added to FIPS CMS first.</p>
</div>

<h3 class="h5 mt-4">What can you do in delivery reporting?</h3>

<h4 class="h6 mt-3">1. Submit performance metrics</h4>
<p>This is how you report on your product's performance:</p>

<ol>
    <li>Navigate to your product's page</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Submit metrics</strong></li>
    <li>Enter values for each metric:
        <ul>
            <li><strong>User satisfaction:</strong> Percentage of satisfied users (0-100%)</li>
            <li><strong>Service availability:</strong> Uptime percentage (0-100%)</li>
            <li><strong>Transaction volumes:</strong> Number of transactions processed</li>
            <li>Other product-specific metrics</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>Add any notes or commentary to provide context</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Submit</strong></li>
</ol>

<div class="card border-success mt-3 mb-3">
    <div class="card-body">
        <h4 class="h6"><i class="fas fa-lightbulb text-warning"></i> Tips for submitting metrics</h4>
        <ul class="mb-0">
            <li>Submit metrics regularly (monthly is typical) to track trends</li>
            <li>Add notes to explain any unusual values or changes</li>
            <li>If you don't have data for a metric, explain why in the notes</li>
            <li>Use consistent measurement approaches for accurate trends</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
</div>

<h4 class="h6 mt-3">2. View performance trends</h4>
<p>After submitting metrics over time, you can view trends:</p>

<ol>
    <li>Navigate to your product's page</li>
    <li>Click <strong>View history</strong> or <strong>Performance trends</strong></li>
    <li>You'll see charts showing how your metrics have changed over time</li>
    <li>Use the date filters to focus on specific time periods</li>
</ol>

<h4 class="h6 mt-3">3. Conduct functional standards assessments</h4>
<p>Demonstrate compliance with DDaT functional standards:</p>

<ol>
    <li>Navigate to <strong>Enterprise reporting → Functional standards</strong></li>
    <li>Click <strong>Conduct assessment</strong></li>
    <li>Select your product and the standard you're assessing against</li>
    <li>For each criterion:
        <ul>
            <li>Select compliance level (not met, partially met, fully met)</li>
            <li>Provide evidence of compliance</li>
            <li>Add notes or explanations</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>Review and submit your assessment</li>
</ol>

<hr class="my-4">

<h2 id="operational-reporting">Operational reporting: Managing risks, issues, actions, and milestones</h2>

<p>Operational reporting (also known as RAID management) helps you track and manage the day-to-day challenges and activities. RAID stands for:</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>R</strong>isks - Things that might go wrong</li>
    <li><strong>A</strong>ctions - Tasks that need doing</li>
    <li><strong>I</strong>ssues - Problems that have occurred</li>
    <li><strong>D</strong>ecisions/Milestones - Key deliverables and deadlines</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="h5 mt-4">Understanding RAID: A simple example</h3>

<p>Let's use a simple scenario to understand how these work together:</p>

<div class="card bg-light mt-3 mb-3">
    <div class="card-body">
        <p class="h6">Scenario: You're managing a web service</p>
        
        <p><strong><i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle text-warning"></i> Risk:</strong> "There's a <em>risk</em> that our database server might run out of storage space in the next 3 months."</p>
        <ul>
            <li>It hasn't happened yet, but it might</li>
            <li>You rate the likelihood and impact</li>
            <li>You plan how to respond (avoid, mitigate, accept, or transfer)</li>
        </ul>
        
        <p class="mt-3"><strong><i class="fas fa-times-circle text-danger"></i> Issue:</strong> "Our search functionality is returning slow results, and users are complaining."</p>
        <ul>
            <li>This is happening right now</li>
            <li>You need to resolve it</li>
            <li>You track its priority and status</li>
        </ul>
        
        <p class="mt-3"><strong><i class="fas fa-tasks text-info"></i> Action:</strong> "Contact the infrastructure team to increase database storage allocation."</p>
        <ul>
            <li>A specific task someone needs to do</li>
            <li>Has a due date and an assigned owner</li>
            <li>Might be linked to a risk or issue</li>
        </ul>
        
        <p class="mt-3"><strong><i class="fas fa-flag text-success"></i> Milestone:</strong> "Complete the performance optimisation work by end of Q2."</p>
        <ul>
            <li>A key deliverable or deadline</li>
            <li>May have multiple risks, issues, and actions associated with it</li>
            <li>Tracks progress towards completion</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
</div>

<h3 class="h5 mt-4">Working with risks</h3>

<h4 class="h6 mt-3">When to create a risk</h4>
<p>Create a risk when you identify something that <strong>could</strong> go wrong or cause problems for your product or project. Risks are about potential future problems.</p>

<h4 class="h6 mt-3">Creating your first risk</h4>
<ol>
    <li>Navigate to <strong>Product governance → Risks</strong></li>
    <li>Click <strong>Create new risk</strong></li>
    <li>Fill in the form:
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Title:</strong> Clear, concise description (e.g., "Database storage capacity may be exceeded")</li>
            <li><strong>Description:</strong> Explain the risk in detail - what could happen and why?</li>
            <li><strong>Product:</strong> Select which product this affects</li>
            <li><strong>Risk types:</strong> Select all that apply (you can choose multiple)
                <ul>
                    <li>Technical risk, operational risk, financial risk, etc.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Risk tier:</strong> Select the appropriate governance level
                <ul>
                    <li>Project-level (affects a single project)</li>
                    <li>Programme-level (affects multiple related projects)</li>
                    <li>Portfolio-level (affects multiple programmes)</li>
                    <li>Department-level (affects departmental objectives)</li>
                    <li>Cross-government (affects multiple departments)</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Business area:</strong> Select your organisational area (optional)</li>
            <li><strong>Impact:</strong> Rate 1-5 (1 = minimal, 5 = severe) - Click the <i class="fas fa-info-circle text-primary"></i> icon for guidance</li>
            <li><strong>Likelihood:</strong> Rate 1-5 (1 = very unlikely, 5 = very likely) - Click the <i class="fas fa-info-circle text-primary"></i> icon for guidance</li>
            <li><strong>Risk owner:</strong> Type a name or email to search for the person responsible</li>
            <li><strong>Response strategy:</strong> How will you handle this risk?
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Avoid:</strong> Change plans to eliminate the risk</li>
                    <li><strong>Mitigate:</strong> Take action to reduce impact or likelihood</li>
                    <li><strong>Transfer:</strong> Move the risk to another party (e.g., insurance)</li>
                    <li><strong>Accept:</strong> Accept the risk and monitor it</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>Click <strong>Create</strong></li>
</ol>

<div class="alert alert-success">
    <p class="mb-0"><i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> <strong>Understanding risk scoring:</strong> COMPASS automatically calculates your risk score by multiplying Impact × Likelihood. A score of 15-25 is critical, 10-14 is high, 5-9 is medium, and 1-4 is low. Click the info icons <i class="fas fa-info-circle text-primary"></i> next to fields for detailed guidance.</p>
</div>

<h3 class="h5 mt-4">Working with issues</h3>

<h4 class="h6 mt-3">When to create an issue</h4>
<p>Create an issue when something <strong>has</strong> gone wrong or is currently causing problems. Issues are about problems happening now.</p>

<h4 class="h6 mt-3">Creating your first issue</h4>
<ol>
    <li>Navigate to <strong>Product governance → Issues</strong></li>
    <li>Click <strong>Create new issue</strong></li>
    <li>Fill in the form:
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Title:</strong> Clear description of the problem</li>
            <li><strong>Description:</strong> Explain what's happening, who's affected, and the impact</li>
            <li><strong>Product:</strong> Select which product is affected</li>
            <li><strong>Severity:</strong> How bad is the problem?
                <ul>
                    <li>Critical (service down, major impact)</li>
                    <li>High (significant impact on users)</li>
                    <li>Medium (noticeable but manageable)</li>
                    <li>Low (minor inconvenience)</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Priority:</strong> How urgently does this need fixing?</li>
            <li><strong>Status:</strong> Usually "Open" for new issues</li>
            <li><strong>Issue owner:</strong> Who is responsible for resolving this?</li>
            <li><strong>Target resolution date:</strong> When should this be fixed by?</li>
            <li><strong>Blocked:</strong> Check this if you can't make progress (e.g., waiting for another team)</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>Click <strong>Create</strong></li>
</ol>

<h4 class="h6 mt-3">Updating issue status</h4>
<p>As you work on resolving an issue, update its status:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Open:</strong> Issue identified, not yet being worked on</li>
    <li><strong>In progress:</strong> Actively working on resolution</li>
    <li><strong>Blocked:</strong> Can't progress due to external dependencies</li>
    <li><strong>Resolved:</strong> Fix implemented, waiting to confirm it's working</li>
    <li><strong>Closed:</strong> Confirmed resolved and no longer an issue</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="h5 mt-4">Working with actions</h3>

<h4 class="h6 mt-3">When to create an action</h4>
<p>Create an action when there's a specific task that needs to be done. Actions are often linked to risks (mitigation actions) or issues (resolution actions), but can also stand alone.</p>

<h4 class="h6 mt-3">Creating your first action</h4>
<ol>
    <li>Navigate to <strong>Product governance → Actions</strong></li>
    <li>Click <strong>Create new action</strong></li>
    <li>Fill in the form:
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Title:</strong> Clear, actionable description (start with a verb: "Contact...", "Review...", "Update...")</li>
            <li><strong>Description:</strong> Explain what needs to be done and why</li>
            <li><strong>Action owner:</strong> Who will do this? (Type to search for staff)</li>
            <li><strong>Action source:</strong> Where did this action come from?
                <ul>
                    <li>Risk (mitigation action)</li>
                    <li>Issue (resolution action)</li>
                    <li>Milestone (delivery action)</li>
                    <li>Service assessment (recommendation)</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Due date:</strong> When must this be completed?</li>
            <li><strong>Priority:</strong> High, medium, or low</li>
            <li><strong>Status:</strong> Not started, in progress, blocked, done, or cancelled</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>Optionally link to related risks, issues, or milestones</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Create</strong></li>
</ol>

<h3 class="h5 mt-4">Working with milestones</h3>

<h4 class="h6 mt-3">When to create a milestone</h4>
<p>Create a milestone for key deliverables, deadlines, or important project phases. Milestones help you track progress towards major goals.</p>

<h4 class="h6 mt-3">Creating your first milestone</h4>
<ol>
    <li>Navigate to <strong>Product governance → Milestones</strong></li>
    <li>Click <strong>Create new milestone</strong></li>
    <li>Fill in the form:
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Title:</strong> Name of the deliverable or milestone</li>
            <li><strong>Description:</strong> What needs to be achieved?</li>
            <li><strong>Product:</strong> Which product does this relate to?</li>
            <li><strong>Target date:</strong> When should this be achieved?</li>
            <li><strong>Status:</strong> Not started, on track, at risk, delayed, complete, or cancelled</li>
            <li><strong>Progress:</strong> Percentage complete (0-100%)</li>
            <li><strong>Milestone owner:</strong> Who is responsible for delivery?</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>Click <strong>Create</strong></li>
</ol>

<hr class="my-4">

<h2 id="your-dashboard">Using your personalised dashboard</h2>

<p>Your COMPASS dashboard is your command centre - it shows everything assigned to you in one place.</p>

<h3 class="h5 mt-4">Understanding your dashboard</h3>

<ol>
    <li>Click <strong>Home</strong> in the left sidebar (or the home icon in the top nav)</li>
    <li>You'll see several tabs:
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Overview:</strong> Summary cards showing all your items at a glance</li>
            <li><strong>Products:</strong> Products where you're listed as a contact</li>
            <li><strong>Issues:</strong> Issues you own</li>
            <li><strong>Risks:</strong> Risks you own</li>
            <li><strong>Actions:</strong> Actions assigned to you</li>
            <li><strong>Milestones:</strong> Milestones you own</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>Each tab shows a count - numbers in red indicate overdue items needing attention</li>
</ol>

<h3 class="h5 mt-4">Using dashboard filters</h3>

<p>The dashboard has powerful filtering to help you focus:</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Time period filters:</strong> View all items, overdue items, items due today, this week, this month, or next month</li>
    <li><strong>Status filters:</strong> Filter by status (open, in progress, complete, etc.)</li>
    <li><strong>Priority filters:</strong> Focus on high-priority or critical items</li>
</ul>

<div class="card border-primary mt-3 mb-3">
    <div class="card-body">
        <h4 class="h6"><i class="fas fa-lightbulb text-warning"></i> Dashboard tips</h4>
        <ul class="mb-0">
            <li>Start each day by checking your dashboard for overdue or urgent items</li>
            <li>Use the "Overdue" filter to see what needs immediate attention</li>
            <li>Red badges indicate overdue items - prioritise these first</li>
            <li>Amber badges indicate items due within 7 days - plan to complete these soon</li>
            <li>Click any item to view details or edit directly from the dashboard</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
</div>

<h3 class="h5 mt-4">Viewing reports</h3>

<p>To see how your products are performing across the portfolio:</p>

<ol>
    <li>Navigate to <strong>Reports</strong> in the left sidebar</li>
    <li>Choose from:
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Risks and issues:</strong> See all risks and issues ranked by product health score</li>
            <li><strong>Analysis:</strong> View visual analysis and identify products needing attention</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>Use the filters to focus on specific products, statuses, or time periods</li>
    <li>Export reports to Excel, PDF, or CSV for sharing with stakeholders</li>
</ol>

